WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:15.120
Hello everyone, I'm Rudy

00:00:15.120 --> 00:00:20.880
Fraser and it brings me a lot of joy to be presenting

00:00:21.260 --> 00:00:30.610
on this topic here at the second atmosphere conference

00:00:31.100 --> 00:00:31.410
.

00:00:31.460 --> 00:00:33.340
It's been really cool to be able to ask people if

00:00:33.350 --> 00:00:37.550
this is their first atmosphere conference and if this is your first

00:00:37.680 --> 00:00:41.960
atmosphere conference, welcome.

00:00:41.960 --> 00:00:44.340
And yeah, I hope that there's something here that you

00:00:44.340 --> 00:00:50.100
can take away and ship something and build something for the community

00:00:50.100 --> 00:00:51.710
and ecosystem.

00:00:51.920 --> 00:00:54.810
So as I said, I'm Rudy Fraser.

00:00:54.810 --> 00:00:57.640
I'm the founder and CEO of Black Sky Algorithms

00:00:57.640 --> 00:00:57.920
.

00:00:57.920 --> 00:01:02.020
I am previously a fellow at the Applied Social Media Lab

00:01:02.020 --> 00:01:03.700
at the Berkman Klein Center.

00:01:03.700 --> 00:01:06.440
I'm the board chair of PAC Collective, which is

00:01:06.440 --> 00:01:11.530
a nonprofit that fiscally hosts about 25 mutual aid groups

00:01:11.670 --> 00:01:13.340
in New York City.

00:01:13.340 --> 00:01:17.080
And I'm an organizer with We the People NYC.

00:01:17.080 --> 00:01:22.240
Black Sky launched about three years ago now.

00:01:22.240 --> 00:01:26.180
And we started off as just a custom feed on the Blue

00:01:26.180 --> 00:01:27.320
Sky app.

00:01:27.320 --> 00:01:32.780
And now has been used by over 2 million people.

00:01:32.780 --> 00:01:36.400
The feeds are used by a quarter million people every month.

00:01:36.530 --> 00:01:39.560
And we are a member supported organization.

00:01:39.660 --> 00:01:44.300
And that member support is really important because the last time that

00:01:44.300 --> 00:01:47.450
I was here at Atmosphere conference, it was just

00:01:47.450 --> 00:01:48.860
me on this slide.

00:01:49.050 --> 00:01:51.820
But now it's our entire team.

00:01:51.820 --> 00:01:52.860
And our entire team is here today.

00:01:52.860 --> 00:02:01.680
So if you see folks with a Black Sky shirt

00:02:02.140 --> 00:02:06.520
on, tell them what's up.

00:02:06.890 --> 00:02:07.190
Yeah.

00:02:07.190 --> 00:02:10.380
And I think that the thesis for Black Sky is that we

00:02:10.380 --> 00:02:15.890
really do believe that App Protocol has these unique properties that allow

00:02:15.890 --> 00:02:20.090
folks to -- it helped us bootstrap a pretty large

00:02:20.260 --> 00:02:21.360
community.

00:02:21.360 --> 00:02:26.590
And we think that we're really interested in helping other folks

00:02:26.590 --> 00:02:31.590
basically do the same thing, leveraging the stuff in the protocol

00:02:31.590 --> 00:02:32.140
.

00:02:32.140 --> 00:02:32.830
Okay.

00:02:32.830 --> 00:02:36.300
So the title of this talk is Groundings with my siblings

00:02:36.300 --> 00:02:36.680
.

00:02:36.680 --> 00:02:39.340
And I want to start by explaining where that comes from.

00:02:39.340 --> 00:02:42.940
Walter Rodney was a Guyanese activist, scholar,

00:02:42.940 --> 00:02:43.340
Pan-Africanist.

00:02:43.340 --> 00:02:47.420
And I think most important for us today, he was a

00:02:47.420 --> 00:02:49.020
practitioner.

00:02:49.020 --> 00:02:53.680
He's best known for how Europe underdeveloped Africa.

00:02:53.680 --> 00:02:56.460
But his earlier work, The Groundings with my brothers,

00:02:56.460 --> 00:02:58.650
is one that changed how I think about what I'm doing

00:02:58.650 --> 00:02:59.340
with Black Sky.

00:02:59.340 --> 00:03:05.340
Rodney was 26 years old, fresh off his PhD teaching

00:03:05.340 --> 00:03:08.140
at the University of the West Indies in Jamaica in 1968

00:03:08.140 --> 00:03:08.300
.

00:03:08.300 --> 00:03:12.000
And he did something that the university and the Jamaican government

00:03:12.000 --> 00:03:13.340
could not understand.

00:03:13.340 --> 00:03:14.540
He left the campus.

00:03:14.540 --> 00:03:20.600
He went into the communities and sat down with Rastaf

00:03:20.620 --> 00:03:21.420
arians.

00:03:21.420 --> 00:03:24.810
People that -- and I think a lot of people have an

00:03:25.060 --> 00:03:28.270
understanding of like Rastafarians in like Bob Marley

00:03:28.270 --> 00:03:31.530
's sense, but Rastafarians in Jamaica are considered

00:03:31.530 --> 00:03:33.020
like -- they're like houseless people.

00:03:33.020 --> 00:03:36.060
They're like the -- they're like gutter punks

00:03:36.060 --> 00:03:36.300
.

00:03:36.410 --> 00:03:38.140
Like they're outcasts.

00:03:38.340 --> 00:03:40.180
And yeah.

00:03:40.530 --> 00:03:43.590
And so he sat down with these folks and they reasoned

00:03:43.590 --> 00:03:44.260
together.

00:03:44.260 --> 00:03:45.920
And that's what grounding is.

00:03:46.000 --> 00:03:49.560
It's a Rastafari concept, sitting down together

00:03:49.560 --> 00:03:50.510
to reason.

00:03:50.510 --> 00:03:54.320
And the part that I keep coming back to is that Rod

00:03:54.320 --> 00:04:00.720
ney insisted that he was the student in those exchanges.

00:04:00.720 --> 00:04:04.170
He said, "I got knowledge from them, real knowledge

00:04:04.170 --> 00:04:07.330
." He went in thinking he had something to teach, and

00:04:07.330 --> 00:04:10.800
he came out understanding that the people closest to the problem already

00:04:10.800 --> 00:04:11.990
had the analysis.

00:04:11.990 --> 00:04:15.130
They didn't -- they just didn't have the platform that

00:04:15.140 --> 00:04:15.720
he had.

00:04:15.740 --> 00:04:19.570
His widow, Patricia, described grounding not as an event,

00:04:19.710 --> 00:04:22.690
but as a practice, a way of living.

00:04:22.690 --> 00:04:27.650
One where academics and activism were integrated and inseparable.

00:04:27.660 --> 00:04:32.700
I'm borrowing this framework because over the last year, I

00:04:32.700 --> 00:04:36.190
feel like I left the code base and went to -- kind

00:04:36.190 --> 00:04:40.720
of did the inverse -- went to college campuses, went to

00:04:40.720 --> 00:04:44.500
conferences, went to community spaces, sat down with people,

00:04:44.500 --> 00:04:48.860
spoke, listened, probably talked to the most people I've

00:04:49.170 --> 00:04:51.500
spoken to in my life in the last year.

00:04:51.500 --> 00:04:57.590
And like Rodney, I learned more from those conversations than

00:04:57.660 --> 00:04:59.750
than I could have given back in those moments.

00:04:59.750 --> 00:05:01.490
And so that's what this talk is about.

00:05:01.630 --> 00:05:04.830
It's like what I heard, what surprised me, what

00:05:04.830 --> 00:05:07.980
we got wrong, and kind of, yeah, what we

00:05:07.980 --> 00:05:10.780
took away from these moments.

00:05:10.780 --> 00:05:15.130
So here's what that grounding looked like in practice: 15

00:05:15.290 --> 00:05:18.750
different cities, several college campuses and schools, a lot of

00:05:18.750 --> 00:05:21.900
times sitting with people who have never heard of App Protocol,

00:05:21.900 --> 00:05:25.730
never heard of Blue Sky, but who cared deeply about the

00:05:25.870 --> 00:05:30.310
same problems that I believe everyone in this room is building towards

00:05:30.310 --> 00:05:30.640
.

00:05:30.640 --> 00:05:34.170
And now I'm grounding with you.

00:05:35.000 --> 00:05:38.810
Really, I should be probably sitting amongst y'all,

00:05:38.810 --> 00:05:39.210
right?

00:05:39.210 --> 00:05:41.560
Like it's instead of just like speaking from the from the

00:05:41.560 --> 00:05:42.020
podium.

00:05:42.100 --> 00:05:47.030
But I want to give you what Rodney gave the people

00:05:47.030 --> 00:05:50.460
he sat with, which is just honesty and his experience.

00:05:50.740 --> 00:05:55.020
There's a tendency in tech circles and communities to only share

00:05:55.020 --> 00:05:58.050
the wins, only share the big fundraisers, and

00:05:58.050 --> 00:06:00.940
I think if you follow me on Blue Sky, Black Sky

00:06:00.940 --> 00:06:03.620
, I tell you when I think we're doing something wrong

00:06:03.620 --> 00:06:03.740
.

00:06:03.740 --> 00:06:09.520
And yeah, and so I don't think you learn from

00:06:09.540 --> 00:06:13.890
just wins or highlight reels.

00:06:13.890 --> 00:06:17.910
I think you learn from losses and from pain.

00:06:17.910 --> 00:06:24.520
The open source community is at least adjacent to the ideal that

00:06:24.700 --> 00:06:27.180
information wants to be free.

00:06:27.180 --> 00:06:31.420
And so this is my giving this information to you for free

00:06:31.420 --> 00:06:34.030
so that you can build something that folks find valuable and you

00:06:34.030 --> 00:06:37.100
don't have to go through the same pain points that we

00:06:37.100 --> 00:06:37.340
had.

00:06:40.380 --> 00:06:41.380
Okay.

00:06:41.380 --> 00:06:45.310
First up, PDSs.

00:06:45.310 --> 00:06:48.440
I think portability is a core premise of the protocol.

00:06:48.780 --> 00:06:52.640
But there's a pattern in how it actually becomes real for

00:06:52.640 --> 00:06:53.100
people.

00:06:53.100 --> 00:06:58.230
So in this chart, you can see, so over time

00:06:58.230 --> 00:07:01.950
, right, this is a chart pulled from Makuba.

00:07:01.950 --> 00:07:03.580
I think it's their name.

00:07:03.580 --> 00:07:09.600
They have this dashboard of independent weekly users posting from non-

00:07:09.600 --> 00:07:11.020
Blue Sky PDSs.

00:07:11.020 --> 00:07:17.650
And that first gray circle there was -- I kind of unintention

00:07:17.860 --> 00:07:22.570
ally posted about giving away invite codes.

00:07:22.570 --> 00:07:24.780
I was talking about giving away invite codes to our mods,

00:07:25.420 --> 00:07:28.540
and then Black Sky was like, there are invite codes?

00:07:28.810 --> 00:07:32.220
What are the invite codes for?

00:07:32.430 --> 00:07:36.090
And so, and so, yeah, so I did the

00:07:36.090 --> 00:07:39.340
like Oprah meme and then we got like 200 replies asking for

00:07:39.340 --> 00:07:40.140
invite codes.

00:07:40.150 --> 00:07:47.170
And at the time, I remember being pretty frustrated with where

00:07:47.170 --> 00:07:50.020
the atmosphere community was at on data portability.

00:07:50.020 --> 00:07:52.870
I feel like there are times when stuff is like treated as

00:07:52.870 --> 00:07:53.820
a solved problem.

00:07:53.820 --> 00:07:56.300
And so, I made a post about it.

00:07:56.720 --> 00:08:01.390
And a day later, I made a video showing how to

00:08:01.420 --> 00:08:05.320
migrate using the GOAT command line tool.

00:08:05.320 --> 00:08:11.480
That video now has 1,000 views on YouTube of just

00:08:11.480 --> 00:08:14.250
like a 45-minute video where I'm just like,

00:08:14.250 --> 00:08:14.700
this is hard.

00:08:14.700 --> 00:08:15.820
You probably don't want to do this.

00:08:15.820 --> 00:08:21.020
And then the very next day, Bailey Townsend shipped

00:08:21.020 --> 00:08:23.340
version 1 of PDS Mover.

00:08:23.350 --> 00:08:31.400
And yeah, and so and

00:08:31.500 --> 00:08:36.300
like you can kind of clearly see that that makes that makes

00:08:36.300 --> 00:08:37.500
a difference, right?

00:08:38.780 --> 00:08:44.150
The purple circle is some band controversies that we won't

00:08:44.150 --> 00:08:45.660
get too, too deep into.

00:08:45.670 --> 00:08:51.030
But, you know, it was, again, a real

00:08:51.240 --> 00:08:52.140
pain point.

00:08:52.140 --> 00:08:54.450
I think sometimes people see things on the internet and they think

00:08:54.450 --> 00:08:57.810
it's like, it maybe doesn't affect real life.

00:08:57.950 --> 00:09:00.990
But again, I'm in all these different places.

00:09:00.990 --> 00:09:04.110
I was at a conference in the Bay Area, this like

00:09:04.110 --> 00:09:05.340
observatory.

00:09:05.620 --> 00:09:09.340
And multiple times in the night, people kept coming up to

00:09:09.340 --> 00:09:11.100
me is like, so what's going on with Link?

00:09:11.100 --> 00:09:15.260
I'm just like, do you know him personally?

00:09:15.260 --> 00:09:17.570
But they just heard about the story.

00:09:17.570 --> 00:09:19.740
And for us, it was very painful.

00:09:19.740 --> 00:09:22.590
It brought our entire mission, like sometimes people like, why

00:09:22.590 --> 00:09:23.580
do you even need a PDS?

00:09:23.580 --> 00:09:27.100
It brought our whole mission into question of like, why do

00:09:27.100 --> 00:09:28.700
you even exist then if this could happen?

00:09:29.120 --> 00:09:33.480
And so it was and it had a real dollar value to

00:09:33.480 --> 00:09:33.750
it.

00:09:33.750 --> 00:09:36.040
Like we ended up shelling out $14,000 to

00:09:36.170 --> 00:09:38.540
like set up an app view server just to like bare metal

00:09:38.540 --> 00:09:38.710
.

00:09:38.710 --> 00:09:41.210
And then went and that's not counting the labor to like

00:09:41.220 --> 00:09:47.850
get all that stuff built and shipped.

00:09:47.850 --> 00:09:51.840
And then the blue circle, which is the big spike,

00:09:51.840 --> 00:09:53.730
is Eurosky launching.

00:09:53.730 --> 00:09:55.340
Shout out to them.

00:09:55.340 --> 00:10:02.000
So you can see all this happened at the end of last

00:10:02.370 --> 00:10:03.220
year.

00:10:03.270 --> 00:10:06.810
And there were just like very specific things people did to change

00:10:06.810 --> 00:10:08.030
the narrative.

00:10:08.030 --> 00:10:10.840
And as I mentioned to Blue Sky folks, like with all

00:10:10.940 --> 00:10:14.130
due respect to Blue Sky, like this was a fully community

00:10:14.330 --> 00:10:15.220
driven effort.

00:10:15.220 --> 00:10:17.900
There was no like outside initiative.

00:10:17.900 --> 00:10:19.950
It was just folks saw a problem.

00:10:19.950 --> 00:10:21.160
They worked on it.

00:10:21.290 --> 00:10:25.940
I know Bailey was like going back and forth with folks figuring

00:10:25.940 --> 00:10:26.960
out how to make it better.

00:10:26.960 --> 00:10:28.220
We were going back and forth.

00:10:28.220 --> 00:10:31.130
I was every invite code was done via my DMs at

00:10:31.150 --> 00:10:31.900
one point.

00:10:31.900 --> 00:10:37.460
So I was literally talking to hundreds of people to like coordinate

00:10:37.730 --> 00:10:37.820
this.

00:10:38.940 --> 00:10:43.040
And so the pattern there is the story is really just like

00:10:43.110 --> 00:10:45.890
there was a tool, but it wasn't accessible to folks

00:10:45.890 --> 00:10:46.330
, right?

00:10:46.330 --> 00:10:48.220
The command line tools didn't move the needle.

00:10:48.220 --> 00:10:51.760
And then it went to this client side Chromium based

00:10:51.760 --> 00:10:53.380
tool that was mobile friendly.

00:10:53.380 --> 00:10:55.100
And that was what folks needed.

00:10:55.100 --> 00:10:58.780
And yeah.

00:10:58.780 --> 00:11:02.490
And so it was just like, to me that felt very

00:11:02.490 --> 00:11:02.920
clear.

00:11:02.920 --> 00:11:05.810
The users that we knew, like they weren't ever going

00:11:05.850 --> 00:11:09.280
to like download the source code and like build something to use

00:11:09.280 --> 00:11:09.680
it.

00:11:09.680 --> 00:11:13.180
You know, it needed to be really clear and concise.

00:11:13.180 --> 00:11:16.660
And we found out from just doing that, like there are

00:11:16.660 --> 00:11:19.980
people using all types of browsers I've never heard of,

00:11:19.990 --> 00:11:22.620
personally.

00:11:22.620 --> 00:11:23.700
And in different scenarios.

00:11:23.700 --> 00:11:25.660
So imagine you got some -- one of our first users who

00:11:25.790 --> 00:11:28.840
migrated, it was like a half a gigabyte blob storage

00:11:28.840 --> 00:11:29.100
.

00:11:29.100 --> 00:11:32.380
Imagine if you're trying to do that client side over like

00:11:32.380 --> 00:11:36.010
a cell phone network with some random browser.

00:11:36.010 --> 00:11:36.700
You know what I mean?

00:11:38.460 --> 00:11:40.130
And so -- and yeah.

00:11:40.130 --> 00:11:42.250
And so -- and then what I think I tilt -- I

00:11:42.250 --> 00:11:44.220
tip my hat to the Eurosky folks.

00:11:44.220 --> 00:11:45.900
What they did was they did it server side.

00:11:45.900 --> 00:11:49.420
And so it was like it just happened in the background for

00:11:49.460 --> 00:11:49.820
the user.

00:11:49.820 --> 00:11:53.020
And it became really turnkey.

00:11:53.070 --> 00:11:55.620
And so we took that inspiration from that and built what became

00:11:55.620 --> 00:11:56.030
move.

00:11:56.030 --> 00:11:56.660
blacksky.

00:11:56.660 --> 00:11:59.100
community which followed that same pattern.

00:12:00.700 --> 00:12:03.940
Also, because we have this community space, we're able

00:12:04.070 --> 00:12:08.850
to like analyze the -- this 20 million record feed database and

00:12:08.850 --> 00:12:12.220
was able to find like the real -- people had real fear

00:12:12.220 --> 00:12:12.540
.

00:12:12.540 --> 00:12:14.750
They had -- they thought that their accounts were going to get

00:12:14.750 --> 00:12:16.700
deleted if they did the migration process.

00:12:16.700 --> 00:12:21.680
And so like another thing that we did was like add social

00:12:21.680 --> 00:12:22.050
proof.

00:12:22.050 --> 00:12:23.140
So like when you go to move.

00:12:23.140 --> 00:12:23.650
blacksky.

00:12:23.690 --> 00:12:27.260
community now, you see how many people are on the

00:12:27.260 --> 00:12:28.220
PDS.

00:12:28.220 --> 00:12:30.860
You see -- and it's sorted by people with big followers

00:12:30.860 --> 00:12:32.640
because people are like, oh, if I have a bigger

00:12:32.640 --> 00:12:33.980
account, how will this work for me?

00:12:33.980 --> 00:12:36.940
So having that kind of social proof.

00:12:36.970 --> 00:12:41.130
But the -- but we found that that was the effective way

00:12:41.340 --> 00:12:44.220
to help people get through the migration.

00:12:44.240 --> 00:12:49.180
And yeah, now our PDS has over 30,000

00:12:49.180 --> 00:12:50.140
accounts on it.

00:12:58.310 --> 00:13:02.650
All right.

00:13:02.650 --> 00:13:03.450
All right.

00:13:03.450 --> 00:13:03.670
The next one.

00:13:03.670 --> 00:13:03.880
A favorite.

00:13:03.880 --> 00:13:04.030
The app.

00:13:04.060 --> 00:13:04.860
bski compatible app view.

00:13:05.320 --> 00:13:08.660
I want to -- this is like an important one for me

00:13:08.660 --> 00:13:12.620
because I think sometimes people point out, I guess, where

00:13:12.680 --> 00:13:15.140
we're at and not necessarily where we want to be going

00:13:15.140 --> 00:13:15.320
.

00:13:15.320 --> 00:13:17.660
Blacksky is not trying to be a micro blogging app

00:13:17.660 --> 00:13:17.740
.

00:13:17.740 --> 00:13:20.050
We're not trying to like compete with like blue sky on

00:13:20.050 --> 00:13:20.540
that.

00:13:20.600 --> 00:13:27.500
The app modality or medium is not important for us.

00:13:28.300 --> 00:13:32.130
But to fulfill the mission of reaching millions of people, but

00:13:32.270 --> 00:13:34.880
being independent, we needed to do this.

00:13:34.880 --> 00:13:36.980
We needed to be able to say that we could do a

00:13:36.980 --> 00:13:38.780
backfill of the entire network.

00:13:38.780 --> 00:13:39.880
It needed to be possible.

00:13:39.880 --> 00:13:41.020
People have said it was done.

00:13:41.020 --> 00:13:43.250
We need to like actually do it.

00:13:43.390 --> 00:13:46.460
And more than anything for me, I need to prove to

00:13:46.460 --> 00:13:48.790
myself this could be done in a way that people would actively

00:13:48.790 --> 00:13:49.260
use it.

00:13:49.260 --> 00:13:51.190
That I would be able to log in, open it up

00:13:51.190 --> 00:13:54.500
every day, and like it would be an effective experience for

00:13:54.500 --> 00:13:54.940
me.

00:13:54.940 --> 00:13:55.890
And it was hard.

00:13:55.890 --> 00:14:00.230
And the things that I knew were going to be frustrating for

00:14:00.580 --> 00:14:03.100
people were the things that ended up being frustrating.

00:14:03.100 --> 00:14:06.650
Some people like to act on the internet that like follower counts

00:14:06.650 --> 00:14:07.660
don't matter.

00:14:07.660 --> 00:14:09.820
The biggest complaint is the follower counts.

00:14:09.820 --> 00:14:11.660
Not matching blue sky.

00:14:13.660 --> 00:14:17.120
To the point where we built a feature that says backfill

00:14:17.120 --> 00:14:21.050
and progress that analyzes what our count says compared to what

00:14:21.050 --> 00:14:23.420
blue skies says compared to what microcosm says.

00:14:23.450 --> 00:14:26.010
And if it's a big enough difference, then we show

00:14:26.010 --> 00:14:26.940
that badge to people.

00:14:26.940 --> 00:14:31.070
To try to get ahead of that and like communicate that they

00:14:31.070 --> 00:14:32.540
're this, we're working on it.

00:14:32.540 --> 00:14:33.580
Right?

00:14:33.580 --> 00:14:35.820
Profile pictures not loading.

00:14:35.820 --> 00:14:37.180
People are like, I can't recognize it.

00:14:37.180 --> 00:14:38.460
I don't know this person by their handle.

00:14:38.460 --> 00:14:40.780
I know them by their profile picture.

00:14:40.780 --> 00:14:41.580
Right?

00:14:41.580 --> 00:14:43.520
So like, if you don't have the profile loading,

00:14:43.520 --> 00:14:45.810
now it's like a weird experience when you're scrolling your

00:14:45.820 --> 00:14:46.300
timeline.

00:14:46.300 --> 00:14:50.170
Stuff like that matters a lot.

00:14:50.210 --> 00:14:53.580
Another thing that we found out that I don't think blue

00:14:53.580 --> 00:14:57.070
sky knew themselves is that if you're banned from blue sky

00:14:57.070 --> 00:15:00.300
, you aren't banned from the image CDN.

00:15:00.300 --> 00:15:02.480
So your profile picture can load.

00:15:02.480 --> 00:15:04.860
But you are banned from the video CDN.

00:15:04.860 --> 00:15:06.490
So you can't upload videos.

00:15:08.940 --> 00:15:11.140
And so now we're like, oh, we got an

00:15:11.140 --> 00:15:11.870
app view.

00:15:11.870 --> 00:15:12.460
Boom.

00:15:12.460 --> 00:15:14.060
We unbanned you.

00:15:14.260 --> 00:15:16.140
Like, we reversed the decision.

00:15:16.140 --> 00:15:17.560
And then they tried to upload a video.

00:15:17.560 --> 00:15:19.100
But we're still using their video CDN.

00:15:19.530 --> 00:15:22.020
And now, once again, we look like we haven't

00:15:22.020 --> 00:15:23.260
fulfilled our mission.

00:15:23.260 --> 00:15:27.610
And it's important to know these things.

00:15:27.700 --> 00:15:31.100
I have on the kind of, just like, I think

00:15:31.100 --> 00:15:33.390
what people think it's like setting up an app view.

00:15:33.390 --> 00:15:35.020
I just want to highlight some of that stuff.

00:15:35.120 --> 00:15:39.610
They think the top is just, like, record hydration.

00:15:39.610 --> 00:15:42.590
Then it's like, there's 42 million people, but

00:15:42.590 --> 00:15:44.240
we don't care about all of them.

00:15:44.250 --> 00:15:47.330
So, like, what's the order that you backfilled

00:15:47.330 --> 00:15:49.020
the people's accounts?

00:15:49.150 --> 00:15:51.260
Then there was, like, stuff was taking too long.

00:15:51.260 --> 00:15:53.680
And then people wanted to use Skeets app with our app

00:15:53.760 --> 00:15:53.930
view.

00:15:53.970 --> 00:15:56.460
And then Skeets app had, like, a timeout

00:15:56.460 --> 00:15:56.880
on it.

00:15:56.880 --> 00:15:59.360
So that was, like, shorter than our timeout.

00:15:59.360 --> 00:16:01.920
So then it was a bunch of 502 errors if you

00:16:01.920 --> 00:16:03.120
tried to use Skeets.

00:16:03.120 --> 00:16:05.020
Notifications is its own thing.

00:16:05.020 --> 00:16:06.880
There was a bug at one point where it was giving you

00:16:06.880 --> 00:16:08.020
duplicate notifications.

00:16:08.020 --> 00:16:08.860
That's annoying.

00:16:08.970 --> 00:16:12.170
Post aggregation, profile aggregation, those are the file

00:16:12.170 --> 00:16:12.620
accounts.

00:16:12.620 --> 00:16:15.260
Handle resolution.

00:16:15.260 --> 00:16:18.530
Being able to, like, include the germ DM.

00:16:18.530 --> 00:16:19.520
Get timeline.

00:16:19.520 --> 00:16:22.560
The further down is, like, the harder the thing's

00:16:22.560 --> 00:16:23.100
got.

00:16:23.220 --> 00:16:25.960
And so get timeline.

00:16:25.980 --> 00:16:29.460
Like, your following feed is, like, really hard.

00:16:29.460 --> 00:16:30.330
Mod appeals.

00:16:30.440 --> 00:16:33.850
So if Blue Sky bans them and they're, like

00:16:33.850 --> 00:16:36.530
, we got -- people were reaching out to us, like

00:16:36.530 --> 00:16:38.250
, which one of you banned us?

00:16:38.380 --> 00:16:43.100
It's a very tricky and complicated thing to answer.

00:16:43.100 --> 00:16:46.150
And then get back to people about, like, you know

00:16:46.150 --> 00:16:48.620
, and again, every single time something like this happens,

00:16:48.620 --> 00:16:50.690
it's, like, if you can't -- if --

00:16:50.690 --> 00:16:54.190
like, why do you exist if we're still, you

00:16:54.190 --> 00:16:55.980
know, experiencing these things?

00:16:55.980 --> 00:16:56.780
OAuth.

00:16:56.780 --> 00:17:00.480
You found out that OAuth doesn't allow you -- if

00:17:00.480 --> 00:17:03.290
you do a social app fork, you're used to being

00:17:03.290 --> 00:17:05.050
able to, like, delete your account, deactivate your

00:17:05.050 --> 00:17:05.500
account.

00:17:05.500 --> 00:17:08.310
We included OAuth to make it, like, really easy

00:17:08.310 --> 00:17:10.460
for anyone, like, even if they're not on our

00:17:10.460 --> 00:17:12.400
PDS, to be able to log into Black Sky.

00:17:13.060 --> 00:17:15.860
But then you couldn't -- the OAuth permissions don't

00:17:15.860 --> 00:17:17.740
allow you to delete your account.

00:17:17.740 --> 00:17:20.490
And so then we're, like -- then we had to

00:17:20.490 --> 00:17:23.370
, like, hack on PDS Gatekeeper to, like

00:17:23.370 --> 00:17:26.250
, do some things where, like, now we ask you

00:17:26.250 --> 00:17:27.760
-- if you're on our PDS, we ask you

00:17:27.760 --> 00:17:28.680
for the password.

00:17:28.680 --> 00:17:30.740
And that allows you to delete the account.

00:17:30.740 --> 00:17:32.930
And if you're not, we send you to the account

00:17:32.980 --> 00:17:33.810
management page.

00:17:33.950 --> 00:17:36.640
But we know that there -- the account management page also,

00:17:36.640 --> 00:17:38.150
like, doesn't have, like, all the things that

00:17:38.150 --> 00:17:38.620
you need.

00:17:38.620 --> 00:17:39.770
Right?

00:17:39.770 --> 00:17:41.060
So pain.

00:17:41.060 --> 00:17:43.260
All this is pain.

00:17:43.940 --> 00:17:48.060
And, again, you, like -- you learn from the

00:17:48.060 --> 00:17:48.210
pain.

00:17:48.420 --> 00:17:51.130
But we experience the pain.

00:17:51.130 --> 00:17:52.840
So now if you want to do this, you know it

00:17:52.840 --> 00:17:53.890
's kind of coming.

00:17:54.000 --> 00:17:54.060
Right?

00:17:54.060 --> 00:17:56.670
That's the whole message of this.

00:17:56.670 --> 00:17:58.730
Post-Nerd at Proto.

00:17:59.700 --> 00:18:08.630
So something

00:18:08.690 --> 00:18:12.330
that I -- yeah, I keep coming back to is,

00:18:12.330 --> 00:18:14.320
like, and I actually got this from Marissa from our

00:18:14.320 --> 00:18:16.290
team, is, like, this concept of, like,

00:18:16.430 --> 00:18:17.420
the job to be done.

00:18:17.420 --> 00:18:21.740
When I'm speaking to people, it's not to do

00:18:21.740 --> 00:18:23.840
at Proto advocacy.

00:18:24.410 --> 00:18:27.570
Like, someone took their time out of their day to hear

00:18:27.570 --> 00:18:29.860
if I can solve the pain point for them.

00:18:29.940 --> 00:18:32.570
I'm not going to pitch you on, you know,

00:18:32.570 --> 00:18:35.000
like -- I'm not going to pitch you on the cause

00:18:35.000 --> 00:18:35.260
.

00:18:35.260 --> 00:18:36.710
I'm supposed to pitch you on, like, I can

00:18:36.720 --> 00:18:38.860
actually fix this thing that you're experiencing.

00:18:38.860 --> 00:18:42.900
So if you -- you know, a lot of the a

00:18:42.900 --> 00:18:44.820
lot of the app protocol devs are the community.

00:18:44.820 --> 00:18:46.380
We're talking about record hydration.

00:18:46.380 --> 00:18:48.360
We're talking about Postgres optimizations.

00:18:48.360 --> 00:18:52.310
You've gotten -- those conversations are very far away from what

00:18:52.310 --> 00:18:53.790
the user is experiencing.

00:18:53.790 --> 00:18:56.380
Unless your user is a developer, which they could be.

00:18:56.380 --> 00:19:00.010
But for us, we're trying to onboard communities of storyt

00:19:00.010 --> 00:19:04.300
ellers who are not sold on decentralized social media.

00:19:04.300 --> 00:19:07.280
They're sold on community building as a tool.

00:19:07.280 --> 00:19:11.800
And then we said that this protocol allows us to get the

00:19:11.810 --> 00:19:13.180
things that you want out of it.

00:19:13.180 --> 00:19:17.970
And yeah, so I spoke to many groups -- many groups

00:19:18.050 --> 00:19:20.630
like this, along with AJ from Northwestern.

00:19:20.630 --> 00:19:22.620
We spoke with Movement for Black Lives.

00:19:22.620 --> 00:19:23.760
We spoke with Slow Factory.

00:19:23.760 --> 00:19:26.140
These are people who, like, they're activist organizations,

00:19:26.140 --> 00:19:29.050
community builders with millions of followers on other platforms.

00:19:29.050 --> 00:19:31.420
They've had people on their teams who've, like,

00:19:31.420 --> 00:19:33.540
built -- they're, like, VPs of engineering at

00:19:33.540 --> 00:19:35.580
, like, social media companies.

00:19:35.610 --> 00:19:37.580
So they understand social media.

00:19:37.700 --> 00:19:40.460
They understand decentralized social media to a degree.

00:19:40.460 --> 00:19:49.210
Very Aligned couldn't close those deals people.

00:19:49.210 --> 00:19:50.340
For various different reasons.

00:19:50.440 --> 00:19:52.540
There were -- and there were -- there were young folks at

00:19:52.540 --> 00:19:57.050
our South by Southwest talk who came to learn how decentralized social

00:19:57.050 --> 00:19:59.340
media can be a part of their content creator journey.

00:19:59.340 --> 00:20:02.370
And if you -- and this -- which was, like,

00:20:02.370 --> 00:20:04.710
a little weird for me because it's, like, you

00:20:04.710 --> 00:20:07.260
're in college and I think maybe do something else.

00:20:07.260 --> 00:20:13.360
But -- And then I got to imagine how disappointing it was

00:20:13.360 --> 00:20:14.300
for you to, like, want to be get -- you

00:20:14.300 --> 00:20:15.310
want to get lit on the internet.

00:20:15.310 --> 00:20:17.260
And then you -- we were talking to you about podcasting

00:20:17.260 --> 00:20:17.690
and RSS.

00:20:17.900 --> 00:20:20.300
You know.

00:20:20.300 --> 00:20:22.480
But, you know, we can't write -- we can

00:20:22.480 --> 00:20:23.800
't write people off.

00:20:23.940 --> 00:20:26.200
If we want this stuff to grow, right?

00:20:26.200 --> 00:20:28.730
Like, another -- I posted about this one example.

00:20:28.730 --> 00:20:30.890
Like, there's a media organization.

00:20:30.890 --> 00:20:33.510
They wanted to reach a particular audience.

00:20:33.510 --> 00:20:36.140
They wanted to reach black Chicagoans.

00:20:36.260 --> 00:20:42.060
We did not lose this deal because the complexity of that protocol

00:20:42.060 --> 00:20:42.260
.

00:20:42.260 --> 00:20:45.110
That wasn't, like, hard to explain to people.

00:20:45.320 --> 00:20:46.950
We didn't lose it because they were, like, oh

00:20:46.950 --> 00:20:47.750
, Mastodon exists.

00:20:47.750 --> 00:20:48.860
That's not why we lost it.

00:20:49.280 --> 00:20:54.180
We -- we lost it because they had a specific need.

00:20:54.180 --> 00:20:56.190
They wanted to reach black Chicagoans.

00:20:56.190 --> 00:20:57.900
It's a decentralized network.

00:20:57.900 --> 00:20:59.620
We don't have all that information.

00:20:59.620 --> 00:21:00.180
You know.

00:21:00.180 --> 00:21:01.080
It's disparate.

00:21:01.080 --> 00:21:02.220
You may be on our PDS.

00:21:02.220 --> 00:21:05.190
But, like, maybe some of you are on a PD

00:21:05.190 --> 00:21:05.440
S.

00:21:05.440 --> 00:21:07.200
Other people are on other PDSs.

00:21:07.200 --> 00:21:08.260
You're on the feed.

00:21:08.340 --> 00:21:10.830
Maybe you're doing -- using a different client app.

00:21:10.830 --> 00:21:11.880
All these different things.

00:21:11.880 --> 00:21:12.730
It makes it hard.

00:21:12.730 --> 00:21:15.030
Like, even if -- even if we kind of knew these

00:21:15.030 --> 00:21:17.810
people existed, there wouldn't be a way to, like

00:21:17.810 --> 00:21:20.220
, do the same -- because they were able to then go

00:21:20.220 --> 00:21:20.870
to Facebook.

00:21:20.870 --> 00:21:23.120
And Facebook's, like, give us $20,000

00:21:23.210 --> 00:21:23.270
.

00:21:23.270 --> 00:21:25.280
We'll get you in front of a million people in the

00:21:25.280 --> 00:21:25.930
next year.

00:21:25.930 --> 00:21:27.580
Can't promise that to people.

00:21:28.010 --> 00:21:31.740
And, yeah.

00:21:31.740 --> 00:21:35.180
And we've only -- we've only ever done inbound

00:21:35.180 --> 00:21:35.400
.

00:21:35.400 --> 00:21:38.160
We think that some things that maybe -- we have some,

00:21:38.240 --> 00:21:40.900
like, theories that if we build out this project called Black

00:21:40.900 --> 00:21:43.450
Sky Cash, it will make the pitch more compelling to people

00:21:43.580 --> 00:21:43.580
.

00:21:43.580 --> 00:21:45.620
It'll make a clear monetization strategy.

00:21:45.620 --> 00:21:48.940
So maybe even if some things aren't necessarily all the way

00:21:48.940 --> 00:21:50.370
there yet, it's like, oh, here's,

00:21:50.370 --> 00:21:52.940
like, a way that you can build community, do democratic

00:21:52.940 --> 00:21:56.070
governance, and have a way for you to fund things.

00:21:56.070 --> 00:21:59.420
But the job to be done is never use AppProto

00:21:59.550 --> 00:21:59.580
.

00:21:59.580 --> 00:22:00.050
Right?

00:22:00.050 --> 00:22:02.240
The job to be done is solve the problem that I have

00:22:02.240 --> 00:22:02.460
.

00:22:02.460 --> 00:22:09.500
And now -- and this one's very important.

00:22:09.900 --> 00:22:14.260
Because we're pitching community builders, we are pitching the atmosphere

00:22:14.260 --> 00:22:15.580
in these spaces.

00:22:15.940 --> 00:22:19.350
Like, I'm not pitching Black Sky, necessarily.

00:22:19.350 --> 00:22:22.620
I'm pitching everyone's projects that are here.

00:22:22.620 --> 00:22:25.660
I know, like, I sometimes talk kind of crazy on

00:22:25.740 --> 00:22:29.740
the internet.

00:22:29.740 --> 00:22:31.390
But I am a lot of people's cheerleaders --

00:22:31.390 --> 00:22:32.120
cheerleader.

00:22:32.130 --> 00:22:34.470
I can't do all the things that y'all have

00:22:34.470 --> 00:22:34.700
done.

00:22:34.700 --> 00:22:40.130
But I do tend to get people to open up about their

00:22:40.260 --> 00:22:41.790
problems.

00:22:41.840 --> 00:22:43.660
And when they do, I pitch your products.

00:22:43.660 --> 00:22:47.620
An example is, like, at South by Southwest, Karen

00:22:47.620 --> 00:22:51.150
Atia, who was fired from the Washington Post because of

00:22:51.150 --> 00:22:53.220
a post on Blue Sky about Charlie Kirk.

00:22:53.300 --> 00:22:55.680
We were talking and she was like, you know, I

00:22:55.680 --> 00:22:58.220
wish there was a way to go live and stream for my

00:22:58.410 --> 00:22:59.370
Blue Sky account.

00:22:59.370 --> 00:23:01.620
And I was like, there is.

00:23:01.620 --> 00:23:03.300
Have you heard of StreamPlace?

00:23:03.300 --> 00:23:05.020
I was like, it's another app.

00:23:05.020 --> 00:23:07.730
And she's like, well, why is it another app

00:23:07.730 --> 00:23:07.900
?

00:23:07.900 --> 00:23:12.090
And so we've had this pitch of, like, you

00:23:12.100 --> 00:23:14.990
have -- you know, there's the whole login with Blue

00:23:14.990 --> 00:23:17.760
Sky, login with app protocol.

00:23:17.830 --> 00:23:20.780
That's even like a second step.

00:23:20.780 --> 00:23:22.870
It's just like, why do I have to go to

00:23:22.870 --> 00:23:25.630
another place if you're saying that I can use this same

00:23:25.630 --> 00:23:26.220
thing?

00:23:26.220 --> 00:23:27.180
Right?

00:23:27.180 --> 00:23:29.740
So to me, this is like a tension in the atmosphere

00:23:29.740 --> 00:23:30.440
right now.

00:23:30.570 --> 00:23:33.800
You can log into a dozen different apps with a single identity

00:23:33.800 --> 00:23:33.980
.

00:23:33.980 --> 00:23:35.080
That's great to us.

00:23:35.080 --> 00:23:37.990
But to everyday people, being told, use this app for

00:23:38.140 --> 00:23:40.760
microblogging, use this one for live streaming, use

00:23:40.760 --> 00:23:43.570
this one for long form content, it doesn't create delight

00:23:43.570 --> 00:23:43.770
.

00:23:43.770 --> 00:23:46.660
It feels like what they already have, a bunch of apps

00:23:46.740 --> 00:23:46.900
.

00:23:46.900 --> 00:23:49.740
And there's no even way to discover all the apps.

00:23:49.740 --> 00:23:52.380
There's not an app store for app protocol.

00:23:52.570 --> 00:23:55.900
So the -- there's no aha moment there for people.

00:23:55.900 --> 00:23:57.520
Like, we have the aha moment.

00:23:57.520 --> 00:23:58.840
We look at the firehose.

00:23:58.840 --> 00:24:00.220
We look at your repository.

00:24:00.220 --> 00:24:02.360
We know that all this data is on one account.

00:24:02.360 --> 00:24:05.760
The user is just like, okay, this is another --

00:24:05.860 --> 00:24:07.780
this is another skin of a thing.

00:24:07.790 --> 00:24:08.450
Right?

00:24:08.450 --> 00:24:13.050
So for me, what would be compelling, and I think

00:24:13.350 --> 00:24:16.920
to the people that I've been talking to, is something

00:24:16.920 --> 00:24:20.060
like an app protocol browser, an app protocol app store.

00:24:20.060 --> 00:24:25.180
Something that turns log in with your identity across many apps from

00:24:25.860 --> 00:24:30.950
developer premise, or a premise, to a user experience.

00:24:30.950 --> 00:24:33.640
So that's the question mark there.

00:24:33.640 --> 00:24:36.780
It's like, I think we talk about app protocol,

00:24:36.780 --> 00:24:38.210
as like, the protocol.

00:24:38.220 --> 00:24:40.340
And we use the comparison to the web.

00:24:40.420 --> 00:24:44.220
Had debates about that even just in this trip.

00:24:44.220 --> 00:24:46.700
And I'm like, so what is the -- well,

00:24:46.700 --> 00:24:48.010
the web has Firefox.

00:24:48.010 --> 00:24:50.680
And I can go to any website with Firefox.

00:24:50.680 --> 00:24:53.460
And it feels really simple, intuitive.

00:24:53.540 --> 00:24:54.100
Right?

00:24:54.100 --> 00:24:57.050
There's no universal app protocol client.

00:24:57.340 --> 00:25:00.890
If you had to download -- the equivalent is like downloading an

00:25:00.970 --> 00:25:02.220
app on your phone.

00:25:02.660 --> 00:25:05.730
But then again, now we're just back to downloading a

00:25:05.730 --> 00:25:06.860
bunch of apps on your phone.

00:25:06.860 --> 00:25:10.860
And if you have logged in with Google, then like,

00:25:10.860 --> 00:25:12.350
as a user, I'm like, what's the difference

00:25:12.350 --> 00:25:12.540
?

00:25:12.550 --> 00:25:16.370
All right.

00:25:16.510 --> 00:25:22.120
Finally, there is a book by Douglas Hofstadter called

00:25:22.320 --> 00:25:23.050
I'm a Strange Loop.

00:25:24.940 --> 00:25:32.810
Oh, recognition.

00:25:33.340 --> 00:25:37.580
Nice.

00:25:37.590 --> 00:25:42.460
Of yourself perceiving the world.

00:25:42.460 --> 00:25:46.400
And that model changes what you perceive, which changes the model

00:25:46.400 --> 00:25:46.540
.

00:25:48.300 --> 00:25:52.340
So when we started using moderation, we used Blue Skies

00:25:52.340 --> 00:25:53.100
Ozone.

00:25:53.100 --> 00:25:55.260
It's open source.

00:25:55.330 --> 00:25:56.360
It works.

00:25:58.140 --> 00:25:59.420
But it wasn't built for us.

00:25:59.420 --> 00:26:00.010
Right?

00:26:00.010 --> 00:26:02.620
It was built for Blue Skies Trust and Safety Team.

00:26:02.620 --> 00:26:08.810
Our moderation team, it started out as like very community moderation

00:26:08.810 --> 00:26:09.260
.

00:26:09.260 --> 00:26:12.540
And we still want that to be that way.

00:26:12.630 --> 00:26:15.090
We're even building more ways that the community can participate in

00:26:15.090 --> 00:26:15.660
moderation.

00:26:15.660 --> 00:26:20.250
It's more like Ozone was built for a particular worldview

00:26:20.350 --> 00:26:22.790
, not necessarily a scale.

00:26:22.830 --> 00:26:27.100
Because we can do peer moderation at scale.

00:26:27.220 --> 00:26:28.940
Reddit does peer moderation at scale.

00:26:28.940 --> 00:26:34.140
It's just a different opinion of how things work.

00:26:34.260 --> 00:26:36.430
And so for us, Dr.

00:26:36.430 --> 00:26:39.950
K, JD, they're community members.

00:26:39.950 --> 00:26:44.540
They weren't reviewing content for a platform.

00:26:44.540 --> 00:26:46.370
They were protecting a space that they're a part of.

00:26:46.380 --> 00:26:50.650
And so Rishi on the team built Acorn.

00:26:50.650 --> 00:26:51.340
And literally...

00:26:51.350 --> 00:26:59.580
And as I understand it, because Rishi is very

00:26:59.580 --> 00:27:02.650
interested in co-working with people, because we're all

00:27:02.650 --> 00:27:03.260
remote right now.

00:27:03.260 --> 00:27:07.780
He and JD got on calls every day and just worked side

00:27:07.780 --> 00:27:08.210
by side.

00:27:08.220 --> 00:27:11.480
And when JD ran into a problem, Rishi built something

00:27:11.610 --> 00:27:12.050
for it.

00:27:12.150 --> 00:27:15.970
And so, yeah.

00:27:16.110 --> 00:27:18.040
And so what you're looking at on the screen is like

00:27:18.140 --> 00:27:21.240
the first thing a moderator sees when they open a session.

00:27:21.240 --> 00:27:23.260
Not a queue, a check-in.

00:27:23.260 --> 00:27:25.420
How are you feeling right now?

00:27:25.420 --> 00:27:26.730
Do you have water nearby?

00:27:26.780 --> 00:27:27.850
You can step away.

00:27:27.850 --> 00:27:29.580
Your well-being comes first.

00:27:29.620 --> 00:27:32.220
There are session goals.

00:27:32.320 --> 00:27:33.930
It could be time-based or item-based.

00:27:33.980 --> 00:27:39.020
So moderators choose how much weight they can take on.

00:27:39.020 --> 00:27:40.620
Because you could just loop, right?

00:27:40.620 --> 00:27:41.710
And just keep going.

00:27:41.710 --> 00:27:44.140
And that could be really, really heavy.

00:27:44.140 --> 00:27:50.340
We're building collaboration tools in it.

00:27:50.460 --> 00:27:52.960
We're building ways for us to govern our community from it

00:27:52.960 --> 00:27:53.140
.

00:27:53.140 --> 00:27:56.230
We're going to build ways to issue badges to our community

00:27:56.380 --> 00:27:57.370
through it.

00:27:57.370 --> 00:27:58.940
Where we use...

00:27:58.940 --> 00:28:01.750
Our feed kind of works like a subreddit.

00:28:01.960 --> 00:28:04.260
So Acorn is going to be built to like manage a

00:28:04.260 --> 00:28:05.970
subreddit where you can remove members.

00:28:05.970 --> 00:28:07.020
You can remove posts.

00:28:07.130 --> 00:28:10.470
You could do this from your phone.

00:28:10.470 --> 00:28:12.100
Our mods...

00:28:12.100 --> 00:28:16.380
Our mods want to moderate from their mobile devices.

00:28:16.680 --> 00:28:19.180
And yeah.

00:28:19.180 --> 00:28:20.160
Ozone doesn't...

00:28:20.220 --> 00:28:21.510
It just doesn't work like that.

00:28:21.510 --> 00:28:23.130
It makes it really difficult to.

00:28:23.130 --> 00:28:24.650
And again, that's not a...

00:28:24.740 --> 00:28:27.450
That's not just because it's some big platform, some

00:28:27.450 --> 00:28:29.020
billion-person platform.

00:28:29.020 --> 00:28:29.730
It's just us.

00:28:29.870 --> 00:28:32.940
We built it the way our users, our community, our

00:28:32.940 --> 00:28:33.820
mods do things.

00:28:33.820 --> 00:28:39.910
And so that's the strange loop.

00:28:39.970 --> 00:28:42.480
Like, you are the user.

00:28:42.700 --> 00:28:45.200
You're also the builder.

00:28:45.200 --> 00:28:51.040
And the thing you build changes your user experience, which changes

00:28:51.330 --> 00:28:52.540
what you build next.

00:28:52.540 --> 00:28:55.240
Toni Morrison said, if the book you want to read doesn

00:28:55.240 --> 00:28:56.890
't exist, you have to write it.

00:28:58.860 --> 00:28:59.740
But it's deeper than that.

00:28:59.740 --> 00:29:01.690
So once you write it, now it's out in the

00:29:01.690 --> 00:29:02.380
world.

00:29:02.380 --> 00:29:03.580
Now it's coming back to you.

00:29:03.580 --> 00:29:03.980
Right?

00:29:03.980 --> 00:29:06.460
So the gift and the recipient keep changing each other.

00:29:06.460 --> 00:29:10.540
So every lesson today comes from the same place.

00:29:10.540 --> 00:29:12.530
We are the user.

00:29:12.530 --> 00:29:13.180
Right?

00:29:13.180 --> 00:29:15.590
I was the first one to migrate to the Black Sky PD

00:29:15.590 --> 00:29:15.850
S.

00:29:15.850 --> 00:29:18.220
I also had the pain when it was just GOAT.

00:29:18.220 --> 00:29:19.340
Right?

00:29:19.380 --> 00:29:22.020
I knew the app you had to work because...

00:29:22.020 --> 00:29:24.350
Like, the way that the community would expect it.

00:29:24.350 --> 00:29:26.280
I knew follower counts had to be right.

00:29:26.280 --> 00:29:28.610
Like, the first app view that I used that was independent

00:29:28.610 --> 00:29:29.580
from Blue Sky.

00:29:29.580 --> 00:29:30.820
It was like, half my followers now.

00:29:30.820 --> 00:29:31.410
This is weird.

00:29:31.420 --> 00:29:32.620
So you just...

00:29:32.620 --> 00:29:34.330
You can predict these things.

00:29:34.330 --> 00:29:34.700
Right?

00:29:34.700 --> 00:29:36.740
And I know we have to...

00:29:36.740 --> 00:29:39.660
We have to get beyond just the dev community.

00:29:39.660 --> 00:29:39.900
Right?

00:29:39.940 --> 00:29:42.540
Like, if we want it to be a big thing,

00:29:42.540 --> 00:29:44.250
like, it has to be fun.

00:29:44.340 --> 00:29:45.660
It has to be cool.

00:29:45.660 --> 00:29:47.120
It has to have different...

00:29:47.730 --> 00:29:49.000
It has to have that delight.

00:29:49.000 --> 00:29:49.380
Right?

00:29:49.380 --> 00:29:50.860
It has to have these aha moments.

00:29:51.040 --> 00:29:54.220
And so, yeah.

00:29:54.280 --> 00:29:55.740
So that's the kind of thing.

00:29:55.740 --> 00:29:57.280
We became...

00:29:57.280 --> 00:29:59.420
We become who we build for.

00:29:59.440 --> 00:30:01.110
And that's not, like, a bug.

00:30:01.320 --> 00:30:02.420
That's, like, the whole point.

00:30:02.420 --> 00:30:04.460
And that's our practice of how we work on things.

00:30:04.560 --> 00:30:14.900
Thank you.
